            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 53-year-old man who looks slightly older than his stated age, with a careful, deliberate way of moving that reflects years of adapting to fluctuating neurologic symptoms. He has a lean build and often shifts his weight before standing, bracing briefly on the arm of a chair to steady himself. A faint tremor appears in his right hand when he is fatigued, and his gait is mildly spastic with reduced left leg swing. During conversation he is alert, thoughtful, and cooperative, though he occasionally pauses to find words when he is tired. His speech is clear but slows late in the day, and he describes a persistent sense of heaviness in his legs, intermittent numbness in his fingertips, and burning neuropathic discomfort along the soles of his feet.\n\nHe works part-time as an accountant after reducing his hours over the last few years because of fatigue and cognitive slowing. He used to enjoy long-distance cycling and weekend hiking, but now limits himself to short rides on a stationary bike and gentle neighborhood walks with a cane on bad days. He remains independent in most activities of daily living, though he plans errands carefully to conserve energy and avoid overheating, which predictably worsens his weakness and blurred vision. He keeps a notebook and phone reminders to compensate for lapses in short-term memory and concentration.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse, who provides emotional support and occasionally helps during symptom flares. He has two adult children who visit regularly and encourage him to stay engaged socially, although he has become more selective about outings because crowded, warm environments quickly exhaust him. He enjoys woodworking in his garage, watching baseball, and maintaining a small vegetable garden, but he now takes frequent rest breaks because prolonged standing worsens leg stiffness and imbalance.\n\nHis diet is generally balanced, though his appetite dips during periods of severe fatigue. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol only occasionally. He tries to follow a home stretching program and attends periodic physical therapy to preserve mobility. Friends describe him as practical and quietly determined; despite frustration about progressive limitations, he remains motivated to continue disease-modifying therapy and symptom management so he can maintain function and independence."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
