            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis approximately 11 years ago after episodes of unilateral optic neuritis, distal paresthesias, and gait imbalance, with MRI showing demyelinating lesions and cerebrospinal fluid positive for oligoclonal bands. Over the past several years, he has had fewer clear relapses but gradual worsening of lower-extremity stiffness, fatigue, urinary urgency, and reduced walking endurance, suggesting a progressive component to his disease course. He reports heat intolerance, intermittent blurred vision, muscle spasms at night, neuropathic burning pain in both feet, and occasional constipation.\n\nHis medical history also includes hypertension that is well controlled without end-organ complications and one prior hospitalization 6 years ago for an MS relapse treated with intravenous corticosteroids. He has never required ventilatory support or feeding assistance. He ambulates independently at home, occasionally using a cane outdoors or during flares. He completed prior courses of outpatient physical therapy focused on gait training and stretching.\n\n{patientName} has no history of tobacco or illicit drug use. He drinks 1-2 alcoholic beverages on some weekends. He sleeps poorly when spasticity is severe and reports chronic fatigue that limits full-time work. He remains adherent with neurology follow-up and is interested in preserving function, reducing relapse risk, and managing day-to-day symptoms that interfere with work and home activities."
